com.cross_ni.cross.db.pojo.ca

Class CADefinitionSet

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.cross_ni.cross.db.pojo.ca.CADefinitionSet

  • @Entity
 @CrossAPI
public class CADefinitionSet
extends Object
    Custom Attribute Definition Set.

    The Cross only defines basic set of attributes for Nodes, Links, IpPools and other entities. These attributes (referred as Core Attributes) are common to all Cross customer deployments.

    In addition to the Core Attributes, many of the Cross entities can have set of Custom Attributes. The Custom Attributes are usually project-specific and vary from customer to customer.

    Example: A typical Core Attribute id Node.name attribute. It is a core attribute, this means that every node has it, whether it's in Cross deployed for Bhutan Telecom or O2 CZ. A custom attribute is an attribute that is usually specific to particular Cross deployment. For instance, nodes of type Building can have attribute TMID in Cross implementation for T-Mobile CZ, but the attribute TMID does not exist in Cross implementation for O2 CZ (another attribute may exist in that particular implementation).

    To explain the Custom Attributes in Cross, we start with CADefinitionSet. The CADefinitionSet contains number of CADefinitions, each CADefinition is a definition of an attribute. The relation between CADefinitionSet and CADefinition is m:n, with CADefinitionSetCADefinition intermediate table. Thus each CADefinitionSet can contain multiple CADefinitions and one CADefinition can be used in multiple CADefinitionSets. For instance, CADefinition for attribute WIDTH(dounle, mm) can be used for custom attributes of Nodes of type NodeType.RACK, NodeType.SHELF, NodeType.ROOM, etc.

    The CADefinitionSet and CADefinitions define structure of the custom attributes, but no actual values. For instance, the CADefinitionSet assigned to a NodeType named NodeType.RACK defines custom attributes for all Nodes of that NodeType, but no actual values are created until a node of type RACK is created. Once the node is created, Cross instantiates the CADefinitionSet, creating CASet.

    The CASet is an instance of CADefinitionSet, containing set of CAValues. Each CAValue contains value for particular CADefinition. There is 1:n relation between CADefinitionSet and CASet, i.e. a CADefinitionSet can have many InlineNewInstanceExpression (CASets). The number of CAValues in CASet is the same as number of CADefinitions in CADefinitionSet (the CAValues hold the values for attributes defined in CADefinitions).

    There number of CASet can be really high, especially for Nodes of type NodeType.LOGICAL_PORT, CustomAddresses, etc... Adding CADefinition to CADefinitionSet that already has many instances can be quite slow, as CAValue needs to be created for each of the CASets.

    Author:
    bigvlad
